Colored Scatterplot Matrix¶

Select a categorical attribute and encode its values with color in the scatterplot matrix (e.g. with altair again or seaborn pairplot).

In [28]:
# Plot the selected attributes again and color code the points by position
poke_sns = pd.DataFrame(df_data, columns=['sp_attack','sp_defense','speed','weight_kg', 'hp','generation', 'is_legendary'])

sns.pairplot(poke_sns, hue="is_legendary")
Out[28]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x7fb371ddaed0>

Interpretation¶

Already in this visualization we are able to see that between there is a little bit of a linear dependancy between speed and attack as well as defense and attack. I have choosen the is_legendary variable instead of the generation for the sake of better distinction of the categorical variables.

Task: Heat Map¶

Select suitable attributes and visualise the data in a heatmap, e.g. with seaborn or altair.

In [29]:
#compute the correlations and take a look at them
corr_poke = poke_sns.corr()

# draw a clustered heatmap using seaborn
sns.clustermap(corr_poke, square=True)

/opt/anaconda3/envs/va_heatmap_scatterplot/lib/python3.7/site-packages/seaborn/matrix.py:1215: UserWarning: ``square=True`` ignored in clustermap
  warnings.warn(msg)
Out[29]:
<seaborn.matrix.ClusterGrid at 0x7fb371ddaad0>

Interpretation¶

As shown in the heatmap, there are no positive correlation with the variable generation as well as weight and speed. As an assumption this makes sense, that the heavy pokemons are not fast. On the other side, it is observable that pokemons with higher attack values tend to have higher defense values. This also accounts for speed and attack. Between weight and lifepoints (hp) and defense there is only a small correlation.
